x4freetext: Versatile Array of Neutron Detectors at Low
Energy (VANDLE) which consisted of scintillators
BC-408 (EJ-200 plastic) of 60 cm (long) x 3 cm (wide)
x 3 cm (deep).
The intrinsic neutron detection efficiency of VANDLE
was determined by a separate measurement of 27Al(d,n)
reaction with a 252Cf source at Ohio Univ.
In the alpha-beam experiment, the detection system
covers 227 msr (21-170 deg at beam right side and
75-150 deg at beam left side) in the alpha-beam
experiment.
Tables 10+11 of INL/EXT-16-38791

x4codes.hlp: University of Notre Dame, Notre Dame, IN, United States of America

x4freetext: alpha-beam experiment
49 nm (29 ug/cm2) thick LaF3 evaporated onto 84 nm
(50 ug/cm2) thick Au. The energy thickness is ~12 keV.
Target thickness (to 2%), stoichiometry and purity
were analyzed by Rutherford back scattering (RBS).
Neutron yield was predicted by MCNP6 and the
experimental cross section was determined by
least-squares fit to minimize the difference between
the predicted and measured angular distribution of
neutron yields for each 24Na level.
This procedure was necessary because the detection
system not detect neutrons below its detection
threshold (~500 keV) and also emitted at angles not
subtended by the system.
EN: Effective laboratory energy of alpha particle in
the centre of the target
EN-RSL: Full energy loss of the beam in the target
Cross section added to account for populated
22Na levels with neutrons below the detection
threshold

x4freetext: 19F-beam experiemnt
4He gas (4000+/-5 mTorr, corresponding to energy
thickness of 5 keV and areal density of 2.6 ug/cm2)
in a windowless recirculating gas target system.
Beam current was determined by detection of
elastically scattered recoil alphas at 45 deg
during 4He(19F,n) measurement.
A separate experiment was performed to determine
elastic scattering alpha yield per Coulomb.
22Na gated neutron yields/Coulomb was normalized  to
22Na yields/Coulomb by scaling factors determined at
four alpha energy ranges, and 22Na gated neutron
yields/Coulomb and 22Na yields/Coulomb were combined.
The combined yields (relative cross sections) were
further normalized to the absolute cross sections
from the alpha-beam experiment.
Si detector (28 cm from the target gas) at 45 deg
for alpha detection.
Daresbury Recoil Separator at 0 deg for
22Na detection with angular acceptance of +/-2.6 deg
which is not sufficient to cover the opening angle of
22Na recoils (4 deg).
EN: Effective laboratory energy of alpha particle in
the centre of the target corresponding to the same
center of mass energy as the laboratory energy of the
fluorine beam
EN-RSL: Full energy loss of the beam in the target
Total uncertainty
Fitting of measured angular dependent yield to
the predicted angular dependent yield simulated by
MCNP
Beam current and target thickness normalization
Yield reproducibility                      (6%)
